        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἅπαξ λεγόμενον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the New Testament, not found in the LXX., and rare in classical Greek. The kindred words, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σκέπη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σκέπας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with their derivatives, are used of the covering or shelter of clothes, or tents, or houses. St. Paul may therefore have used an uncommon word in order to comprise the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "two",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " necessaries of raiment and house, though Huther thinks this \"more than improbable.\" The use of the word \"covering\" in the R.V. seems designed to favor this double application. Ellicott thinks the word \"probably only refers to clothing.\" Alford says, \"Some take ' covering' of both clothing and dwelling, perhaps rightly.\" If one knew where St. Paul got the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σκεπάσματα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from, one could form a more decided opinion as to his meaning. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "We shall be therewith content",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀρκεσθήσομεθα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The proper meaning of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀρκεῖσθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " followed by a dative is \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " be content with\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 13:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). There is probably a covert hortative force in the use of the future here. 1 Timothy 6:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
